article.description: Jamal Mashburn scored 13 of his 23 points in the final quarter to lead the Hornets to their sixth straight win, 97-92 over the Phoenix Suns.
article.headline: Hornets crash boards, outrebound 14th straight foe
article.linkText: Hornets continue cleaning glass, win sixth straight
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Jamal Mashburn had 13 points in the fourth quarter and didn't even want to talk about offense.
Mashburn

The New Orleans star and his teammates were more impressed with their rebounding in a 97-92 win over the Phoenix Suns on Saturday night that stretched the Hornets' winning streak to six games. The Hornets have outrebounded 14 straight opponents, including a 56-33 advantage against the Suns. They had more defensive rebounds (38) than Phoenix's total. "We've been doing that consistently after the All-Star break, and we're really continuing to eat the glass,'' said Mashburn, who finished with 23 points and nine assists. "That's a part of defense itself when the other team doesn't get the opportunity to score.'' Phoenix got within 93-92 on two foul shots by Shawn Marion with 29 seconds to play, but, after a timeout, Courtney Alexander put up an 18-footer that bounced high off the front rim and dropped through with 9.8 seconds to play. On the Suns' last chance to tie, Joe Johnson missed a jumper and Alexander got the rebound, was fouled and made two free throws with 2.2 seconds to go. P.J. Brown had 12 points and a season-high 19 rebounds for New Orleans, Robert Traylor contributed 13 points and 12 rebounds off the bench, and David Wesley and George Lynch had 12 points each. The 6-foot-8 Lynch, starting at guard because control of the offense has shifted to Mashburn since Baron Davis' knee surgery in January, also had seven rebounds, all offensive. The Hornets are 10-3 in Lynch's run as a regular. "When we went with the big lineup, George Lynch, that's what changed things around,'' Hornets coach Paul Silas said. "Our guys are just relentless on the boards.'' Alexander had six of his 10 points in the fourth quarter, and Charlotte's reserves outscored the Suns bench 34-16. "The bench was key, led by Tractor,'' Brown said, referring to Traylor. "They did a great job for us. Without them, there's no way we won this game tonight. I'm just thankful they could come in and give us what they gave, because they gave us big efforts.'' Marion had 23 points for Phoenix, which lost for the fifth time in six games. For the Suns, Amare Stoudemire scored 19 points, Johnson had 17 and Stephon Marbury had 14 points and 13 assists. The Hornets made up a four-point deficit in the first 2:29 of the fourth quarter, surging to a 75-73 lead after three-point plays by Traylor and Mashburn 21 seconds apart. Marbury tied it with two free throws before Mashburn scored six points to lead a 10-4 spurt that opened an 85-49 lead with 6:15 left. "We knew they were going to come out physical,'' Stoudemire said. "We were prepared for it. It just slipped away from us.'' Mashburn had five points during a 16-6 run that began in the first quarter and carried the Hornets to a 38-26 lead with 9:28 left in the second. Then, when the Suns closed within 42-36 with 4:46 to go after two short jumpers by Marbury and an 18-footer by Johnson, Mashburn sank a 3-pointer 24 seconds later. The Suns trailed 49-46 at halftime and took their first lead, 56-55, on a 3-pointer by Marion with 8:15 left in the third quarter. When the 13-0 run ended with Johnson's baseline jumper, Phoenix was ahead 61-55 with 6:33 to play. The Hornets came back to lead one more time, but four free throws by Casey Jacobsen and two baskets by Tom Gugliotta allowed the Suns to take a 71-67 lead into the fourth quarter. "I'd like to forget the first and fourth quarter,'' Suns coach Frank Johnson said. "I liked what we did in the second and third.''

Game notes
Suns G Penny Hardaway will meet with orthopedist Robert Wilson on Monday for an evaluation that could clear him to return to the lineup this week. He had thumb surgery seven weeks ago, but said the pain was manageable even when hit on the thumb in practice Friday. ... The Hornets are tied with Minnesota for the second-best active winning streak in the NBA, trailing only Philadelphia's eight-game roll. ... Wesley has scored in double figures in 27 straight games.
